cs.SI, cs.IR, cs.SOC, cs.DL, cs.HC 

This paper discusses the dynamics of user behavior and recommendations on the World Wide Web, which falls under the category of social search and information retrieval. Therefore, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also discusses the power law distribution of site visits, which is a common topic in the study of complex systems and networks, making cs.SOC (Social and Economic Networks) a likely sub-category as well. The paper also mentions conducting an empirical study of user behavior, which could fall under cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). Finally, the paper discusses the discovery of new sites by users, which could fall under cs.DL (Digital Libraries).
